sections.content:
CSS uses a simple pattern:

```css
selector {
    property: value;
    property: value;
}
```

Example:
```css
h1 {
    color: blue;
    font-size: 32px;
    text-align: center;
}
```

- **Selector**: What to style (`h1`, `.class`, `#id`)
- **Property**: What to change (`color`, `font-size`)
- **Value**: The new setting (`blue`, `32px`)

Create a file called `styles.css`:

```css
/* Reset some defaults */
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    padding: 20px;
}

h1 {
    color: #333;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

p {
    color: #666;
    margin-bottom: 15px;
}
```

Link it to your HTML and watch your page transform!

CSS supports multiple color formats:

```css
/* Named colors */
color: red;
color: tomato;
color: darkslategray;

/* Hex codes (most common) */
color: #ff0000;     /* Red */
color: #333;        /* Short for #333333 */

/* RGB and RGBA */
color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
color: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5);  /* 50% transparent */

/* HSL (Hue, Saturation, Lightness) */
color: hsl(0, 100%, 50%);     /* Red */
```

**Common color properties:**
- `color`: Text color
- `background-color`: Background
- `border-color`: Border color

Good color palettes typically include:

- **Primary color**: Your brand/main color
- **Secondary color**: Complementary accent
- **Neutral colors**: Grays for text and backgrounds
- **Success/Error**: Green and red for feedback

**Tips:**
- Use 2-3 main colors, not 10
- Ensure sufficient contrast for readability
- Use tools like Coolors.co to generate palettes

```css
:root {
    --primary: #2563eb;
    --secondary: #f59e0b;
    --dark: #1f2937;
    --light: #f3f4f6;
}
```

Control how text looks:

```css
body {
    /* Font family with fallbacks */
    font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Arial, sans-serif;

    /* Size */
    font-size: 16px;

    /* Weight (boldness) */
    font-weight: 400;  /* normal */
    font-weight: 700;  /* bold */

    /* Line spacing */
    line-height: 1.6;

    /* Letter spacing */
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
}

h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;  /* Relative to root size */
    font-weight: bold;
}
```

The default behavior is confusing. Fix it with:

```css
* {
    box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

Now `width: 200px` means the TOTAL width is 200px, including padding and border. This makes layouts much more predictable.

**Always add this to your stylesheets!**

Shorthand properties save typing:

```css
/* All four sides */
margin: 10px;

/* Vertical | Horizontal */
margin: 10px 20px;

/* Top | Horizontal | Bottom */
margin: 10px 20px 30px;

/* Top | Right | Bottom | Left (clockwise) */
margin: 10px 20px 30px 40px;

/* Individual sides */
margin-top: 10px;
margin-left: 20px;
```

Same shortcuts work for `padding`.

The `display` property controls how elements flow:

```css
/* Block: Takes full width, stacks vertically */
display: block;

/* Inline: Flows with text, no width/height */
display: inline;

/* Inline-block: Flows inline but accepts width/height */
display: inline-block;

/* None: Completely hidden */
display: none;

/* Flex: Modern layout (next lesson!) */
display: flex;
```

Understanding display is key to controlling layout.

Control vertical alignment with `align-items`:

```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    height: 200px;
    align-items: flex-start;  /* Top */
    align-items: center;      /* Middle */
    align-items: flex-end;    /* Bottom */
    align-items: stretch;     /* Fill height (default) */
}
```

**Perfect centering in 3 lines:**
```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
}
```

Change the main axis direction:

```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;            /* Horizontal (default) */
    flex-direction: column;         /* Vertical */
    flex-direction: row-reverse;    /* Right to left */
}
```

Allow items to wrap to new lines:
```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 20px;  /* Space between items */
}
```

`gap` is much cleaner than adding margins to each item!

Control individual items:

```css
.item {
    flex-grow: 1;    /* Grow to fill space */
    flex-shrink: 0;  /* Don't shrink */
    flex-basis: 200px; /* Starting size */
}

/* Shorthand */
.item {
    flex: 1;  /* Grow equally */
}

/* Override alignment for one item */
.special-item {
    align-self: flex-end;
}
```

Create responsive grids without media queries:

```css
.container {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
    gap: 20px;
}
```

This creates as many 250px+ columns as will fit, automatically adjusting for screen size. Perfect for card layouts!

- `auto-fit`: Creates columns to fill the space
- `minmax(250px, 1fr)`: Each column is at least 250px

Make items span multiple cells:

```css
.wide-item {
    grid-column: span 2;  /* Span 2 columns */
}

.tall-item {
    grid-row: span 2;     /* Span 2 rows */
}

.big-item {
    grid-column: span 2;
    grid-row: span 2;     /* 2x2 block */
}
```

Or specify exact positions:
```css
.item {
    grid-column: 1 / 3;   /* From line 1 to line 3 */
    grid-row: 2 / 4;      /* From line 2 to line 4 */
}
```

Apply styles based on screen size:

```css
/* Base styles (mobile first) */
.container {
    padding: 10px;
}

/* Tablets (768px and up) */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
    .container {
        padding: 20px;
    }
}

/* Desktops (1024px and up) */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .container {
        padding: 40px;
        max-width: 1200px;
        margin: 0 auto;
    }
}
```

**Mobile-first**: Start with mobile styles, add complexity for larger screens.

Standard screen size breakpoints:

```css
/* Mobile: 0 - 767px (base styles) */

/* Tablet */
@media (min-width: 768px) { }

/* Desktop */
@media (min-width: 1024px) { }

/* Large desktop */
@media (min-width: 1280px) { }
```

Don't obsess over exact numbers - test on real devices and adjust as needed.

Common responsive layout patterns:

**Stack on mobile, side-by-side on desktop:**
```css
.card-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 20px;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
    .card-grid {
        grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .card-grid {
        grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    }
}
```

**Or use auto-fit for automatic responsiveness:**
```css
.card-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 20px;
}
```

Create a file called `script.js`:

```javascript
// This is a comment
console.log('Hello, JavaScript!');

// Variables
let name = 'Sarah';
const age = 25;

// String template
console.log(`Hi, I'm ${name} and I'm ${age} years old.`);

// Alert (popup)
alert('Welcome to my website!');
```

Open your browser's console (F12 → Console) to see the output.

Three ways to declare variables:

```javascript
// let - can be reassigned
let score = 0;
score = 10;  // OK

// const - cannot be reassigned
const name = 'Sarah';
name = 'John';  // ERROR!

// var - old way, avoid using
var oldWay = 'outdated';
```

**Best practice:**
- Use `const` by default
- Use `let` only when you need to reassign
- Never use `var`

JavaScript has several data types:

```javascript
// String (text)
const name = 'Sarah';
const greeting = "Hello!";
const message = `Hi, ${name}`; // Template literal

// Number (integers and decimals)
const age = 25;
const price = 19.99;

// Boolean (true/false)
const isLoggedIn = true;
const hasAccess = false;

// Null (intentionally empty)
const data = null;

// Undefined (not yet assigned)
let result;
console.log(result);  // undefined

// Array (list of items)
const colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'];

// Object (key-value pairs)
const person = {
    name: 'Sarah',
    age: 25
};
```

Common string operations:

```javascript
const text = 'Hello, World!';

// Length
text.length;  // 13

// Case
text.toUpperCase();  // 'HELLO, WORLD!'
text.toLowerCase();  // 'hello, world!'

// Finding text
text.includes('World');  // true
text.indexOf('World');   // 7

// Extracting parts
text.slice(0, 5);   // 'Hello'
text.split(', ');   // ['Hello', 'World!']

// Template literals (best for combining)
const name = 'Sarah';
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`;  // 'Hello, Sarah!'
```

Functions bundle code for reuse:

```javascript
// Function declaration
function greet(name) {
    return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

// Call the function
greet('Sarah');  // 'Hello, Sarah!'

// Arrow function (modern syntax)
const greet = (name) => {
    return `Hello, ${name}!`;
};

// Short arrow function
const greet = (name) => `Hello, ${name}!`;

// Multiple parameters
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
add(5, 3);  // 8
```

Make decisions with if/else:

```javascript
const age = 18;

if (age >= 21) {
    console.log('Can drink alcohol');
} else if (age >= 18) {
    console.log('Can vote');
} else {
    console.log('Still a minor');
}

// Comparison operators
===  // Equal (use this, not ==)
!==  // Not equal
>    // Greater than
<    // Less than
>=   // Greater or equal
<=   // Less or equal

// Logical operators
&&   // AND
||   // OR
!    // NOT
```

Shorthand for simple if/else:

```javascript
// Instead of:
let message;
if (isLoggedIn) {
    message = 'Welcome back!';
} else {
    message = 'Please log in';
}

// Use ternary:
const message = isLoggedIn ? 'Welcome back!' : 'Please log in';

// Great for JSX/React
const button = isLoading ? 'Loading...' : 'Submit';
```

Repeat code with loops:

```javascript
// For loop
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i);  // 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}

// For...of (arrays)
const colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'];
for (const color of colors) {
    console.log(color);
}

// forEach (arrays)
colors.forEach((color) => {
    console.log(color);
});

// While loop
let count = 0;
while (count < 3) {
    console.log(count);
    count++;
}
```

First, select elements to work with:

```javascript
// By ID (returns one element)
const header = document.getElementById('header');

// By CSS selector (returns first match)
const btn = document.querySelector('.btn');
const nav = document.querySelector('nav');

// Multiple elements (returns NodeList)
const items = document.querySelectorAll('.item');
const links = document.querySelectorAll('a');

// Loop through multiple
items.forEach(item => {
    console.log(item.textContent);
});
```

`querySelector` and `querySelectorAll` are the most versatile.

Modify text and HTML:

```javascript
const title = document.querySelector('h1');

// Change text content
title.textContent = 'New Title';

// Change HTML content
title.innerHTML = 'Hello <strong>World</strong>';

// Change attributes
const link = document.querySelector('a');
link.href = 'https://google.com';
link.setAttribute('target', '_blank');

// Get attribute
const src = document.querySelector('img').getAttribute('src');
```

Modify CSS dynamically:

```javascript
const box = document.querySelector('.box');

// Individual styles
box.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
box.style.padding = '20px';
box.style.borderRadius = '10px';

// Add/remove CSS classes (better approach)
box.classList.add('active');
box.classList.remove('hidden');
box.classList.toggle('open');  // Add if missing, remove if present
box.classList.contains('active');  // true/false

// Replace class
box.classList.replace('old-class', 'new-class');
```

**Best practice:** Use `classList` methods instead of inline styles.

Add and remove elements dynamically:

```javascript
// Create new element
const newItem = document.createElement('li');
newItem.textContent = 'New Item';
newItem.classList.add('list-item');

// Add to page
const list = document.querySelector('ul');
list.appendChild(newItem);        // Add at end
list.prepend(newItem);            // Add at start
list.insertBefore(newItem, list.children[1]); // Add at position

// Remove element
const oldItem = document.querySelector('.delete-me');
oldItem.remove();

// Remove all children
list.innerHTML = '';
```

Listen for user actions:

```javascript
const button = document.querySelector('button');

// Click event
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('Button clicked!');
});

// With function reference
function handleClick() {
    console.log('Clicked!');
}
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);

// Remove listener
button.removeEventListener('click', handleClick);
```

Event listeners receive an event object:

```javascript
button.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    event.target;           // Element that was clicked
    event.preventDefault(); // Stop default behavior
});

// Useful for forms
const form = document.querySelector('form');
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault(); // Stop form from refreshing page
    // Handle form data...
});

// Useful for keyboard
document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    console.log(e.key);  // Which key was pressed
    if (e.key === 'Escape') {
        closeModal();
    }
});
```

A common interactive pattern:

```html
<button class="menu-btn">Menu</button>
<nav class="menu hidden">...</nav>
```

```css
.hidden { display: none; }
```

```javascript
const menuBtn = document.querySelector('.menu-btn');
const menu = document.querySelector('.menu');

menuBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    menu.classList.toggle('hidden');

    // Update button text
    const isOpen = !menu.classList.contains('hidden');
    menuBtn.textContent = isOpen ? 'Close' : 'Menu';
});

// Close menu when clicking outside
document.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    if (!menu.contains(e.target) && e.target !== menuBtn) {
        menu.classList.add('hidden');
    }
});
```

